level is really, I
think, deeply at the core

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:24.450 align:middle line:84%
of this materialistic,
consumptive characteristic

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:27.000 align:middle line:84%
of our culture and the
destruction it's causing.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:28.110 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:29:28.110 --> 00:29:30.060 align:middle line:84%
And it's because of
the way we think,

00:29:30.060 --> 00:29:32.550 align:middle line:84%
because we're driven to
do those things because we

00:29:32.550 --> 00:29:34.080 align:middle line:90%
feel like we need to keep up.

00:29:34.080 --> 00:29:36.600 align:middle line:84%
The old phrase was, "Keep
up with the Joneses."

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:39.780 align:middle line:84%
And now it's really gone to a
much greater extent than even

00:29:39.780 --> 00:29:42.520 align:middle line:90%
in the '50s, '60s, and '70s.

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:45.600 align:middle line:84%
It's a matter of diminishing
returns, I guess you could say,

00:29:45.600 --> 00:29:50.010 align:middle line:84%
that we probably benefited
from a lot of the material

00:29:50.010 --> 00:29:53.940 align:middle line:84%
and health and other gains
that our society provided us.

00:29:53.940 --> 00:29:56.820 align:middle line:84%
But then, if we continue
to go faster and faster

00:29:56.820 --> 00:29:59.100 align:middle line:84%
and feel like we
need more and more,

00:29:59.100 --> 00:30:01.503 align:middle line:84%
we disconnect ourselves
from our surroundings.

00:30:01.503 --> 00:30:03.420 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about
disconnecting from nature.

00:30:03.420 --> 00:30:08.160 align:middle line:84%
Well, one aspect of nature that
would disconnect ourselves from

00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:10.120 align:middle line:90%
is a much slower pace of life.

00:30:10.120 --> 00:30:10.920 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:13.650 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And so we come to
consider that the only way

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:16.860 align:middle line:84%
to live is faster and faster
or as fast as we're going now,

00:30:16.860 --> 00:30:20.048 align:middle line:84%
at least, and to purchase
more and more new items.

00:30:20.048 --> 00:30:22.340 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And we're being
persuaded to do this through

00:30:22.340 --> 00:30:25.490 align:middle line:84%
the media machine
that we're bathed in.

00:30:25.490 --> 00:30:26.805 align:middle line:90%
Suggestions are everywhere.

00:30:26.805 --> 00:30:28.430 align:middle line:84%
You can't drive down
a street in a city

00:30:28.430 --> 00:30:31.490 align:middle line:84%
and not have suggestions
coming at you as to what

00:30:31.490 --> 00:30:32.750 align:middle line:90%
you should be consuming next.

00:30:32.750 --> 00:30:38.210 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the documentary I love
is called "Century of Self,"

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:42.110 align:middle line:84%
absolutely brilliant, talking
about the art of persuasion

00:30:42.110 --> 00:30:44.240 align:middle line:84%
starting in the 1920s
and '30s and what's

00:30:44.240 --> 00:30:46.130 align:middle line:84%
happened to our
cultures as a result

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:52.208 align:middle line:84%
of these persuasive forces that
put us into a consumptive mode.

00:30:52.208 --> 00:30:53.750 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's all
we're really being

00:30:53.750 --> 00:30:55.310 align:middle line:90%
encouraged to do is to consume.

00:30:55.310 --> 00:30:56.720 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:30:56.720 --> 00:30:58.250 align:middle line:84%
And if you were to
look at that way,

00:30:58.250 --> 00:31:01.530 align:middle line:84%
then we're being prodded to be
dissatisfied with the things

00:31:01.530 --> 00:31:02.330 align:middle line:90%
that we have.

00:31:02.330 --> 00:31:03.290 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes, absolutely.

00:31:03.290 --> 00:31:05.332 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And I'm wondering
if it's possible that,

00:31:05.332 --> 00:31:08.510 align:middle line:84%
about this time, we, in
fact, are starting to become

00:31:08.510 --> 00:31:12.110 align:middle line:84%
dissatisfied at being
constantly dissatisfied.

00:31:12.110 --> 00:31:14.340 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yes, that's
a perfect way to put it.

00:31:14.340 --> 00:31:17.280 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And I wonder if younger
generations are, in fact,

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:21.680 align:middle line:84%
at that point where there
are notable trends where less

00:31:21.680 --> 00:31:25.430 align:middle line:84%
homeownership and car ownership
and so forth and that it might

00:31:25.430 --> 00:31:29.690 align:middle line:84%
be part of a new understanding,
a new awareness of who we are

00:31:29.690 --> 00:31:33.410 align:middle line:84%
and what is meaningful because
we've become dissatisfied

00:31:33.410 --> 00:31:35.547 align:middle line:84%
at being prodded
to be dissatisfied.

00:31:35.547 --> 00:31:37.130 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Dissatisfied--
I love that.

00:31:37.130 --> 00:31:38.460 align:middle line:90%
That's a perfect way to put it.

00:31:38.460 --> 00:31:40.070 align:middle line:84%
And I see evidence
of this, as well,

00:31:40.070 --> 00:31:42.320 align:middle line:84%
particularly in the
younger generations where

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:46.760 align:middle line:84%
they're wanting to do more,
not necessarily own so much.

00:31:46.760 --> 00:31:48.830 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, future
generations are always

00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:52.320 align:middle line:84%
the key to any kind of healing
process that's going to happen.

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:53.680 align:middle line:90%
And I think you're right.

00:31:53.680 --> 00:31:54.800 align:middle line:90%
I see that.

00:31:54.800 --> 00:31:57.140 align:middle line:84%
We're not wanting to
be manipulated and told

00:31:57.140 --> 00:31:59.960 align:middle line:84%
what to do in the
ways generations

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:02.692 align:middle line:90%
up until now have accepted.

00:32:02.692 --> 00:32:03.900 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: I think that's true.

00:32:03.900 --> 00:32:06.500 align:middle line:84%
And relating it a little bit
to what we were talking about

00:32:06.500 --> 00:32:08.420 align:middle line:84%
earlier with this whole
understanding of Earth

00:32:08.420 --> 00:32:14.540 align:middle line:84%
as a system and the wisdom
that our ancestors had,

00:32:14.540 --> 00:32:19.190 align:middle line:84%
I feel like we do need to link
this new trend of young people

00:32:19.190 --> 00:32:22.490 align:middle line:84%
to both of those things,
the scientific understanding

00:32:22.490 --> 00:32:25.040 align:middle line:84%
of Earth as living
system and the fact

00:32:25.040 --> 00:32:27.890 align:middle line:84%
that all of our
forbearers have understood

00:32:27.890 --> 00:32:31.220 align:middle line:84%
Earth and our relationship
to be different, because then

00:32:31.220 --> 00:32:34.070 align:middle line:84%
their desire to do
things differently

00:32:34.070 --> 00:32:38.090 align:middle line:84%
is rooted in some
real firm foundation

00:32:38.090 --> 00:32:39.870 align:middle line:84%
rather than just
kind of reactive.

00:32:39.870 --> 00:32:40.670 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right.

00:32:40.670 --> 00:32:43.170 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: My worry would be that
if it's just reactive, well,

00:32:43.170 --> 00:32:45.770 align:middle line:84%
then once they kind of discover
that it doesn't work for them

00:32:45.770 --> 00:32:47.210 align:middle line:84%
in any way, shape,
or form, well,

00:32:47.210 --> 00:32:49.830 align:middle line:84%
then they'll just get
back on the bandwagon.

00:32:49.830 --> 00:32:51.890 align:middle line:84%
But if they
rediscover things that

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:56.030 align:middle line:84%
are really meaningful and really
true in all sense of the word,

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:57.710 align:middle line:84%
then they have
something that they

00:32:57.710 --> 00:33:00.952 align:middle line:84%
can lay a groundwork
of their life upon.

00:33:00.952 --> 00:33:03.410 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: One of the things
I'm really encouraged about is

00:33:03.410 --> 00:33:07.220 align:middle line:84%
there are some new magazines
and journals coming out that are

00:33:07.220 --> 00:33:11.180 align:middle line:84%
more lifestyle oriented that
really promote a life much

00:33:11.180 --> 00:33:14.330 align:middle line:84%
closer to nature, whether
it's doing your own gardening,

00:33:14.330 --> 00:33:19.730 align:middle line:84%
knitting your own sweaters,
and whatever it is,

00:33:19.730 --> 00:33:22.430 align:middle line:84%
planting your own, be
attracting flowers.

00:33:22.430 --> 00:33:24.380 align:middle line:84%
That's really a
huge new trend right

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:26.380 align:middle line:90%
now in the magazine business.

00:33:26.380 --> 00:33:28.088 align:middle line:10%
And one of my
favorites is called--

00:33:28.088 --> 00:33:29.630 align:middle line:10%
I think it called
"Mary Jane's Farm."

00:33:29.630 --> 00:33:31.670 align:middle line:10%
I absolutely love it--
great little articles

00:33:31.670 --> 00:33:35.330 align:middle line:10%
on living closer to Earth
and things that matter.

00:33:35.330 --> 00:33:37.100 align:middle line:84%
So I think that
trend is starting

00:33:37.100 --> 00:33:40.910 align:middle line:84%
to happen in earnest now because
people want to feel meaning

00:33:40.910 --> 00:33:44.570 align:middle line:84%
again, tired of just consuming,
consuming, consuming.

00:33:44.570 --> 00:33:47.550 align:middle line:84%
I asked this earlier, and we
didn't really talk about it--

00:33:47.550 --> 00:33:49.550 align:middle line:84%
do you have, in your
own mind, an idea

00:33:49.550 --> 00:33:54.920 align:middle line:84%
of what a green economy,
an organic, workable, green

00:33:54.920 --> 00:33:56.855 align:middle line:90%
economy can look like?

00:33:56.855 --> 00:33:58.730 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Well, I certainly
do in my own mind,

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:00.170 align:middle line:84%
and I could sketch
out that a little.

00:34:00.170 --> 00:34:00.710 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah, I'd like that.

00:34:00.710 --> 00:34:03.140 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: But I think that the
most important part would be

00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:06.590 align:middle line:84%
for us to co-create it so
that it works for everyone.

00:34:06.590 --> 00:34:08.780 align:middle line:84%
Most notably, some
examples could

00:34:08.780 --> 00:34:12.949 align:middle line:84%
serve as a starting point, and
then we need to go beyond that.

00:34:12.949 --> 00:34:16.770 align:middle line:84%
I've often touted the
work of William McDonough,

00:34:16.770 --> 00:34:17.570 align:middle line:90%
for instance.

00:34:17.570 --> 00:34:21.000 align:middle line:84%
He's known as the Green Dean
at the University of Virginia.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.810 align:middle line:84%
And he works with
various industries

00:34:23.810 --> 00:34:26.900 align:middle line:84%
to take what they had been doing
that might have been horribly

00:34:26.900 --> 00:34:29.780 align:middle line:84%
polluting and very
unsustainable and at least take

00:34:29.780 --> 00:34:32.360 align:middle line:84%
those first steps
towards making it

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:35.400 align:middle line:84%
something that could be
sustainable into the future.

00:34:35.400 --> 00:34:38.030 align:middle line:84%
So for instance, his
three guiding principles

00:34:38.030 --> 00:34:41.360 align:middle line:84%
are use daily solar
incoming energy,

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:44.280 align:middle line:84%
so renewable energy-- and
that's almost a no-brainer,

00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:46.760 align:middle line:84%
but it has to be accompanied
with other things.

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:52.190 align:middle line:84%
One of the two other principles
he uses is waste equals food,

00:34:52.190 --> 00:34:53.719 align:middle line:84%
and what he really
means is that we

00:34:53.719 --> 00:34:57.290 align:middle line:84%
have to do away with the
idea of waste completely.

00:34:57.290 --> 00:34:59.820 align:middle line:84%
So in whatever we
do in our economy,

00:34:59.820 --> 00:35:03.680 align:middle line:84%
if there was a byproduct of
some process, manufacturing

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:07.130 align:middle line:84%
or other, but it had
to be designed where

00:35:07.130 --> 00:35:10.760 align:middle line:84%
that byproduct was useful
for some other product

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:14.630 align:middle line:84%
or some other process, then
we'd be fundamentally changing

00:35:14.630 --> 00:35:17.450 align:middle line:84%
our economy to begin with--
so if that really was the way

00:35:17.450 --> 00:35:19.420 align:middle line:90%
we designed things.

00:35:19.420 --> 00:35:23.680 align:middle line:84%
And then his last principle
was called honor diversity.

00:35:23.680 --> 00:35:25.870 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lot of
talk about honoring

00:35:25.870 --> 00:35:29.870 align:middle line:84%
human diversity these days,
which is absolutely necessary.

00:35:29.870 --> 00:35:32.600 align:middle line:84%
But what if we honor the
diversity of our whole place?

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:35.260 align:middle line:84%
So in a region that we
lived, we honored the fact

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:38.380 align:middle line:84%
that it has this climate
and these resources

00:35:38.380 --> 00:35:42.490 align:middle line:84%
and this kind of setting,
like topography and everything

00:35:42.490 --> 00:35:44.950 align:middle line:84%
about a place, the
animals and plants.

00:35:44.950 --> 00:35:48.040 align:middle line:84%
We would figure out ways
to live in that region,

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:50.780 align:middle line:84%
in that place, that are far
different than how we do things

00:35:50.780 --> 00:35:51.580 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:35:51.580 --> 00:35:53.538 align:middle line:84%
And it would look a little
different everywhere

00:35:53.538 --> 00:35:54.980 align:middle line:90%
you go because of that.

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:57.460 align:middle line:84%
So even though that's
not the be-all, end-all,

00:35:57.460 --> 00:36:01.360 align:middle line:84%
I think this kind of thinking
is the starting point

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:03.530 align:middle line:90%
for designing a new economy.

00:36:03.530 --> 00:36:07.570 align:middle line:84%
And if kids get excited about
this and say, we can do this,

00:36:07.570 --> 00:36:10.690 align:middle line:84%
and we're going to arm ourselves
with both outlook and facts

00:36:10.690 --> 00:36:14.720 align:middle line:84%
that will help us do this, then
we're that much further ahead.

00:36:14.720 --> 00:36:15.790 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Absolutely.

00:36:15.790 --> 00:36:17.950 align:middle line:84%
And even the efforts,
even though we're not

00:36:17.950 --> 00:36:19.870 align:middle line:84%
going to get into a
political discussion here,

00:36:19.870 --> 00:36:23.170 align:middle line:84%
but even the efforts of
the new enthusiastic people

00:36:23.170 --> 00:36:27.190 align:middle line:84%
entering Congress and going
for the New Green Deal,

00:36:27.190 --> 00:36:29.380 align:middle line:84%
this is hopeful
that this is even

00:36:29.380 --> 00:36:31.070 align:middle line:84%
being brought into
the conversation,

00:36:31.070 --> 00:36:34.012 align:middle line:84%
as soon as they kind of
hop into their new seats

00:36:34.012 --> 00:36:36.220 align:middle line:84%
and are warming up their
seats in Congress, that they

00:36:36.220 --> 00:36:39.250 align:middle line:84%
want to hop on this notion
and make this such a priority.

00:36:39.250 --> 00:36:41.500 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course, you get
all the immature behavior

00:36:41.500 --> 00:36:44.650 align:middle line:84%
and backlash where the
news says, oh, we're

00:36:44.650 --> 00:36:46.923 align:middle line:84%
going to lose our hamburgers
and our way of life

00:36:46.923 --> 00:36:48.340 align:middle line:84%
and our milkshakes
and everything.

00:36:48.340 --> 00:36:50.710 align:middle line:84%
It's just, again,
this whole need

00:36:50.710 --> 00:36:54.640 align:middle line:84%
to have to divide
people into these really

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:57.220 align:middle line:90%
almost caricature-ish camps.

00:36:57.220 --> 00:36:58.390 align:middle line:90%
That has to go.

00:36:58.390 --> 00:37:01.218 align:middle line:84%
We have to not support
these interests anymore.

00:37:01.218 --> 00:37:02.260 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's a big one.

00:37:02.260 --> 00:37:02.880 align:middle line:90%
Just unplug.

00:37:02.880 --> 00:37:03.760 align:middle line:90%
Don't give them our money.

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:04.930 align:middle line:90%
Don't give them our time.

00:37:04.930 --> 00:37:06.400 align:middle line:90%
Don't give them our attention.

00:37:06.400 --> 00:37:09.610 align:middle line:84%
But it is encouraging to
me that this is happening.

00:37:09.610 --> 00:37:10.420 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:37:10.420 --> 00:37:14.170 align:middle line:84%
And with the Green New Deal, if
we could accompany new thoughts

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:18.590 align:middle line:84%
like that with new interests and
abilities to talk to each other

00:37:18.590 --> 00:37:21.430 align:middle line:84%
so that when we talk
about a Green New Deal

00:37:21.430 --> 00:37:24.250 align:middle line:84%
we know that we're talking about
an economy-- and an economy

00:37:24.250 --> 00:37:27.310 align:middle line:90%
isn't an evil thing inherently.

00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:29.710 align:middle line:84%
Whatever we do into the
future, our business

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:32.510 align:middle line:84%
will be whatever
economy we produce.

00:37:32.510 --> 00:37:35.620 align:middle line:84%
And so our main idea is to
try to talk to each other

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:39.550 align:middle line:84%
and figure out the best ways
to proceed rather than putting

00:37:39.550 --> 00:37:41.780 align:middle line:84%
each other in these
caricature-ish camps

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:42.580 align:middle line:90%
that you describe.

00:37:42.580 --> 00:37:43.380 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:45.730 align:middle line:84%
I mean, a bipartisan
committee on what would that

00:37:45.730 --> 00:37:50.080 align:middle line:84%
look like-- how can we begin
to incorporate industry

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:54.160 align:middle line:84%
and our future economic growth
in with these principles that

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:56.130 align:middle line:84%
are absolutely
needed at this time?

00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:57.940 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, to me
it's encouraging

00:37:57.940 --> 00:38:01.583 align:middle line:84%
that, even if it's all being
treated so ridiculously,

00:38:01.583 --> 00:38:03.250 align:middle line:84%
it's important that
it's even coming up.

00:38:03.250 --> 00:38:04.050 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:38:04.050 --> 00:38:07.780 align:middle line:84%
And I think it could go
faster if we did one thing,

00:38:07.780 --> 00:38:11.500 align:middle line:84%
and that is to make part
of our education system,

00:38:11.500 --> 00:38:13.000 align:middle line:84%
especially at the
high-school level,

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:17.620 align:middle line:84%
not to not do it elsewhere,
but to get kids thinking about

00:38:17.620 --> 00:38:20.260 align:middle line:84%
whatever their career is,
whatever their own skills

00:38:20.260 --> 00:38:24.400 align:middle line:84%
and aptitudes are, that they not
only can but they must be part

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:27.530 align:middle line:84%
of redesigning and
imagining a new economy--

00:38:27.530 --> 00:38:28.330 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: I agree.

00:38:28.330 --> 00:38:31.270 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: --rather than just
having some kids that maybe

00:38:31.270 --> 00:38:33.820 align:middle line:84%
think that they want to be
environmentally minded go

00:38:33.820 --> 00:38:37.930 align:middle line:84%
into some kind of environmental
science as if that, by itself,

00:38:37.930 --> 00:38:38.990 align:middle line:90%
would fix the world.

00:38:38.990 --> 00:38:39.250 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:38:39.250 --> 00:38:40.050 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right.

00:38:40.050 --> 00:38:42.370 align:middle line:84%
If you love fashion and
you want to be a fashion

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:44.830 align:middle line:84%
designer as a young
girl, figure out a way

00:38:44.830 --> 00:38:48.220 align:middle line:84%
to make it work so it
doesn't rely on $0.65 an hour

00:38:48.220 --> 00:38:51.640 align:middle line:84%
sweatshop workers, for
example, and hemp materials

00:38:51.640 --> 00:38:52.628 align:middle line:90%
and all of this.

00:38:52.628 --> 00:38:53.920 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't agree with you more.

00:38:53.920 --> 00:38:55.660 align:middle line:84%
High school educate--
that level where

00:38:55.660 --> 00:38:58.990 align:middle line:84%
people are lit up and ready to
choose, somewhat, some of them,

00:38:58.990 --> 00:39:00.430 align:middle line:90%
their path in life.

00:39:00.430 --> 00:39:03.440 align:middle line:84%
What a perfect way to
start planting those seeds.

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:04.240 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:39:04.240 --> 00:39:07.180 align:middle line:84%
To do that, what we started
talking about with a Gaia

00:39:07.180 --> 00:39:12.400 align:middle line:84%
principle and the Gaia idea is
not an esoteric sideline thing.

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:17.440 align:middle line:84%
It's understanding how this
world works as a living system,

00:39:17.440 --> 00:39:19.970 align:middle line:84%
and then understanding
ourselves as part of that,

00:39:19.970 --> 00:39:23.050 align:middle line:84%
and then getting into the really
complex emotional connections

00:39:23.050 --> 00:39:24.100 align:middle line:90%
that we have.

00:39:24.100 --> 00:39:28.360 align:middle line:84%
That's where we often venture
over into things like metaphor,

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:31.960 align:middle line:84%
and myth, and
religion, et cetera,

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:34.781 align:middle line:84%
that those things
are important, too,

00:39:34.781 --> 00:39:39.920 align:middle line:84%
to our ultimate aim to live well
on this Earth into the future.

00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:43.540 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So what happens
with Darwinism at this point,

00:39:43.540 --> 00:39:46.990 align:middle line:84%
survival of the fittest,
dominance and so forth?

00:39:46.990 --> 00:39:49.690 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Well, that's a really
interesting thing to bring up,

00:39:49.690 --> 00:39:54.970 align:middle line:84%
too, because I feel like
our current economy is still

00:39:54.970 --> 00:39:57.320 align:middle line:84%
basically running on
Social Darwinism--

00:39:57.320 --> 00:39:58.120 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: I agree.

00:39:58.120 --> 00:40:01.720 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: --that phrase that the
industrialists themselves came

00:40:01.720 --> 00:40:03.910 align:middle line:84%
up with to describe
what they were doing.

00:40:03.910 --> 00:40:06.250 align:middle line:84%
But it still is
the way we think.

00:40:06.250 --> 00:40:10.940 align:middle line:84%
It's that the world is simply
and only run on competition.

00:40:10.940 --> 00:40:11.740 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Exactly.

00:40:11.740 --> 00:40:14.980 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Competition is a
big part of how life works,

00:40:14.980 --> 00:40:19.950 align:middle line:84%
but the kind of Gaian
mirror image to that is that

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:23.460 align:middle line:90%
we're also a symbiotic system.

00:40:23.460 --> 00:40:27.510 align:middle line:84%
So we have symbiosis,
in human terms,

00:40:27.510 --> 00:40:31.650 align:middle line:84%
cooperation, kind of
working with competition

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:33.150 align:middle line:90%
and natural selection.

00:40:33.150 --> 00:40:35.940 align:middle line:10%
And Lynn Margulis, who is one
of the scientists who really

00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:38.760 align:middle line:10%
supported the Gaia
theory during her life,

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:42.390 align:middle line:10%
had a phrase that she used, and
it went something like this--

00:40:42.390 --> 00:40:47.760 align:middle line:10%
it was, symbiosis wrote
the symphony of life,

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:51.820 align:middle line:10%
and natural selection edited it.

00:40:51.820 --> 00:40:52.696 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Edited it.

00:40:52.696 --> 00:40:54.450 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Edited it.

00:40:54.450 --> 00:40:58.020 align:middle line:84%
And what that tells us is
that if we had a story that

00:40:58.020 --> 00:41:02.400 align:middle line:84%
accompanied how the world
really works that wasn't Social

00:41:02.400 --> 00:41:07.110 align:middle line:84%
Darwinism but was a social
understanding of ourselves

00:41:07.110 --> 00:41:10.800 align:middle line:84%
as part of a living
planet, then we'd

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:13.410 align:middle line:84%
be in a completely
different place in order

00:41:13.410 --> 00:41:16.980 align:middle line:84%
to imagine ourselves
into the future.

00:41:16.980 --> 00:41:20.250 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And in doing
so, we can't cut technology

00:41:20.250 --> 00:41:24.095 align:middle line:84%
and technological advancement
out of the argument.

00:41:24.095 --> 00:41:24.895 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:41:24.895 --> 00:41:26.520 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Or the
debate, I should say.

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:28.810 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And of course,
technology could also be seen

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:29.610 align:middle line:90%
for what it is.

00:41:29.610 --> 00:41:33.460 align:middle line:84%
Technology is everything we
do to manipulate and change

00:41:33.460 --> 00:41:34.260 align:middle line:90%
our world.

00:41:34.260 --> 00:41:36.660 align:middle line:84%
And so, for instance,
when we did education

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:39.840 align:middle line:84%
about ancient cultures
at a nature center

00:41:39.840 --> 00:41:41.910 align:middle line:84%
that I used to work
at, we would talk

00:41:41.910 --> 00:41:45.150 align:middle line:84%
how an atlatl, a
spear-thrower, is a technology.

00:41:45.150 --> 00:41:46.020 align:middle line:90%
It really is.

00:41:46.020 --> 00:41:48.840 align:middle line:84%
It's not just that
technologies are computers.

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:53.490 align:middle line:84%
It's everything that we design
and make and use that changes

00:41:53.490 --> 00:41:54.960 align:middle line:90%
our world.

00:41:54.960 --> 00:41:56.430 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I don't know why
this is kind of flipping

00:41:56.430 --> 00:41:57.388 align:middle line:90%
into my head right now.

00:41:57.388 --> 00:41:58.890 align:middle line:84%
But I'm thinking
about here we look

00:41:58.890 --> 00:42:02.580 align:middle line:84%
at something like eBay
or Amazon or something

00:42:02.580 --> 00:42:05.070 align:middle line:84%
that was to allow the average
person to get together

00:42:05.070 --> 00:42:07.850 align:middle line:84%
with another person and sell
their goods directly and so

00:42:07.850 --> 00:42:08.650 align:middle line:90%
forth.

00:42:08.650 --> 00:42:10.590 align:middle line:84%
And now you have
incredible levels

00:42:10.590 --> 00:42:14.370 align:middle line:84%
of sabotage and
competition and people

00:42:14.370 --> 00:42:17.010 align:middle line:84%
scanning for sales
in a warehouse,

00:42:17.010 --> 00:42:19.170 align:middle line:84%
buying up the
inventory, putting it

00:42:19.170 --> 00:42:21.990 align:middle line:84%
on Amazon to sell for
a few dollar markup,

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.150 align:middle line:84%
and then knocking
out their competition

00:42:24.150 --> 00:42:28.110 align:middle line:84%
by arranging for bad reviews
on their product and so forth.

00:42:28.110 --> 00:42:29.970 align:middle line:90%
It's like everything.

00:42:29.970 --> 00:42:32.160 align:middle line:84%
It comes down to this
whole notion, as you were

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:34.020 align:middle line:90%
talking about, of competition.

00:42:34.020 --> 00:42:36.960 align:middle line:84%
At what point do we start
looking at cooperation

00:42:36.960 --> 00:42:38.760 align:middle line:90%
as our model for living?

00:42:38.760 --> 00:42:41.370 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, everybody wants to
have their share of the pie.

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:44.640 align:middle line:84%
But do you have to have it
over every other person that's

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:45.760 align:middle line:90%
offering a similar thing?

00:42:45.760 --> 00:42:46.560 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:48.570 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: How do we work
that out in our minds?

00:42:48.570 --> 00:42:51.345 align:middle line:84%
How would you teach
this in high school?

00:42:51.345 --> 00:42:53.970 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Well, as far as solving
something like that short term

00:42:53.970 --> 00:42:59.350 align:middle line:84%
with something as complex as
Google or Amazon, et cetera,

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:00.150 align:middle line:90%
it's hard to say.

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:04.180 align:middle line:84%
But there are some basic
tenets I think we could follow,

00:43:04.180 --> 00:43:07.260 align:middle line:84%
and that is that we can't keep
speeding up-- that's one--

00:43:07.260 --> 00:43:12.120 align:middle line:84%
and that we do have to
have balance and separation

00:43:12.120 --> 00:43:14.140 align:middle line:90%
of powers, if you will.

00:43:14.140 --> 00:43:17.040 align:middle line:84%
And so if it was up to
me, I would start teaching

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:20.610 align:middle line:84%
in first grade, let alone
into high school, the idea

00:43:20.610 --> 00:43:22.695 align:middle line:90%
of the negative feedback loop.

00:43:22.695 --> 00:43:23.820 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Talk about that.

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:27.090 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And the negative
feedback loop is how any system

00:43:27.090 --> 00:43:30.220 align:middle line:84%
works, whether it's our
body or a mechanical system.

00:43:30.220 --> 00:43:33.420 align:middle line:84%
It's where if you go too
far in one direction,

00:43:33.420 --> 00:43:36.630 align:middle line:84%
you're drawn back
towards a healthy center.

00:43:36.630 --> 00:43:38.410 align:middle line:84%
And then if you go
back the other way,

00:43:38.410 --> 00:43:40.620 align:middle line:84%
then you're drawn back
towards that healthy center.

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:44.400 align:middle line:84%
A most familiar example would
be a thermostat, of course.

00:43:44.400 --> 00:43:47.200 align:middle line:84%
But in our own bodies,
say, our blood sugar

00:43:47.200 --> 00:43:51.630 align:middle line:84%
is regulated throughout the day
by our body sensing blood sugar

00:43:51.630 --> 00:43:54.240 align:middle line:84%
levels and kicking insulin
in and then stopping

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:56.520 align:middle line:84%
the production of
insulin, et cetera.

00:43:56.520 --> 00:43:59.830 align:middle line:84%
And when and if that negative
feedback loop breaks down,

00:43:59.830 --> 00:44:00.630 align:middle line:90%
we're diseased.

00:44:00.630 --> 00:44:02.800 align:middle line:90%
We have diabetes.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:06.390 align:middle line:84%
And if we understood that that
is the way everything works,

00:44:06.390 --> 00:44:10.230 align:middle line:84%
then we could design systems
that don't go too fast

00:44:10.230 --> 00:44:12.930 align:middle line:84%
and don't consume too
much, et cetera, et cetera.

00:44:12.930 --> 00:44:15.870 align:middle line:84%
One of the points
of optimism I have

00:44:15.870 --> 00:44:19.080 align:middle line:84%
for being able to talk
to each other about this

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:23.070 align:middle line:84%
is one time having seen in a
biology textbook the yin yang

00:44:23.070 --> 00:44:27.610 align:middle line:84%
symbol juxtaposed right next
to a negative feedback loop.

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:31.795 align:middle line:84%
And it struck me that, yes,
these two are the same things,

00:44:31.795 --> 00:44:35.700 align:middle line:84%
that they're the idea of
living in a balance where

00:44:35.700 --> 00:44:37.890 align:middle line:84%
you don't go too
far out on the ends

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:40.440 align:middle line:90%
and you restore to a center.

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:42.630 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lot
of wisdom there,

00:44:42.630 --> 00:44:44.340 align:middle line:84%
and there's a lot of
scientific reality

00:44:44.340 --> 00:44:45.800 align:middle line:90%
there that we could build on.

00:44:45.800 --> 00:44:47.050 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: I absolutely agree.

00:44:47.050 --> 00:44:49.920 align:middle line:84%
And in terms of human
consciousness, the notion

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:52.740 align:middle line:84%
of thriving without
it having to be

00:44:52.740 --> 00:44:56.550 align:middle line:84%
at the expense of
either nature or one

00:44:56.550 --> 00:44:58.920 align:middle line:84%
another is another
thing, I mean,

00:44:58.920 --> 00:45:01.860 align:middle line:84%
that has to start being
inculcated into our thinking.

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:03.270 align:middle line:90%
We can all thrive.

00:45:03.270 --> 00:45:05.430 align:middle line:84%
This is a very
rich, complex world.

00:45:05.430 --> 00:45:09.240 align:middle line:84%
All of us have such interesting
areas of genius and talents

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:11.640 align:middle line:84%
that we want to bring
forward, that there really

00:45:11.640 --> 00:45:15.600 align:middle line:84%
is room for everybody in
an organic-rich society.

00:45:15.600 --> 00:45:17.670 align:middle line:84%
Instead, it's being
kind of whittled down

00:45:17.670 --> 00:45:21.760 align:middle line:84%
to just a few positions that
you can train for in college.

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:25.090 align:middle line:84%
And so to encourage that
richness, that unique divine

00:45:25.090 --> 00:45:28.180 align:middle line:84%
genius in each individual
expressing itself,

00:45:28.180 --> 00:45:30.460 align:middle line:84%
just the joy of that
expression hopefully

00:45:30.460 --> 00:45:33.070 align:middle line:84%
can start supplanting
the need to win

00:45:33.070 --> 00:45:35.348 align:middle line:90%
at the expense of someone else.

00:45:35.348 --> 00:45:37.390 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And I do think
that that winning aspect,

00:45:37.390 --> 00:45:40.510 align:middle line:84%
that that competitive aspect
is not only a part of nature

00:45:40.510 --> 00:45:43.000 align:middle line:84%
overall, but it's a part
of our human nature,

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.640 align:middle line:84%
but that we can't see
it as the only thing.

00:45:45.640 --> 00:45:49.840 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, if we also
see that part of our thriving

00:45:49.840 --> 00:45:52.840 align:middle line:90%
is a drawing back, as well--

00:45:52.840 --> 00:45:56.680 align:middle line:84%
we are awake during the
day, and then we sleep,

00:45:56.680 --> 00:46:00.400 align:middle line:84%
and we eat, and then we have
had enough, and we stop eating.

00:46:00.400 --> 00:46:02.440 align:middle line:84%
And that's where the joy
in that comes from, not

00:46:02.440 --> 00:46:04.000 align:middle line:84%
from continuing
to stuff yourself.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:04.800 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right.

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:08.230 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: So if we can get
in the mindset that thriving

00:46:08.230 --> 00:46:12.430 align:middle line:84%
in our culture means that we
might have all sorts of nice

00:46:12.430 --> 00:46:14.600 align:middle line:84%
things and consume
to a certain point,

00:46:14.600 --> 00:46:18.700 align:middle line:84%
but there is a point beyond
which we as both individuals

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:22.030 align:middle line:84%
and a society, somehow as
we work things out together,

00:46:22.030 --> 00:46:24.130 align:middle line:90%
have to draw back from that.

00:46:24.130 --> 00:46:28.212 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, that's my
kind of hope for--

00:46:28.212 --> 00:46:29.420 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: It's my hope, too.

00:46:29.420 --> 00:46:33.898 align:middle line:84%
And the notion of
competition, I don't think

00:46:33.898 --> 00:46:36.190 align:middle line:84%
there's anything wrong with
kind of healthy competition

00:46:36.190 --> 00:46:40.190 align:middle line:84%
that's in this kind of good
sported way between people.

00:46:40.190 --> 00:46:42.460 align:middle line:84%
But that's not what
we're talking about here.

00:46:42.460 --> 00:46:44.290 align:middle line:84%
Our culture has gone
a different way,

00:46:44.290 --> 00:46:46.180 align:middle line:84%
and it's that kind
of winning over

00:46:46.180 --> 00:46:48.370 align:middle line:84%
someone versus just
doing your very best

00:46:48.370 --> 00:46:50.360 align:middle line:84%
and thriving that
I'm talking about.

00:46:50.360 --> 00:46:52.000 align:middle line:90%
And I think you are, as well.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:54.740 align:middle line:84%
And a little bit ago, you said--
this isn't an esoteric concept

00:46:54.740 --> 00:46:56.740 align:middle line:84%
you were talking about,
but I'm going to take it

00:46:56.740 --> 00:46:58.157 align:middle line:90%
into an esoteric arena.

00:46:58.157 --> 00:46:59.740 align:middle line:84%
And if you're not
comfortable with it,

00:46:59.740 --> 00:47:02.740 align:middle line:84%
just say, hey, not
my wheelhouse, OK?

00:47:02.740 --> 00:47:06.580 align:middle line:84%
So it's been said by some
of the fairly well-known,

00:47:06.580 --> 00:47:11.200 align:middle line:84%
more spiritual guides and so
forth that the changes that are

00:47:11.200 --> 00:47:12.430 align:middle line:90%
happening on Earth--

00:47:12.430 --> 00:47:14.740 align:middle line:84%
remember everything around
the turn of the century?

00:47:14.740 --> 00:47:17.170 align:middle line:84%
We were going to go through
a polarity shift, and life

00:47:17.170 --> 00:47:19.210 align:middle line:84%
as we knew it would
be over and so forth.

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:20.430 align:middle line:90%
That hasn't happened.

00:47:20.430 --> 00:47:22.250 align:middle line:84%
Yes, Earth does go
through pole shifts.

00:47:22.250 --> 00:47:24.380 align:middle line:90%
It will happen sooner or later.

00:47:24.380 --> 00:47:27.790 align:middle line:84%
But I remember in
one session from--

00:47:27.790 --> 00:47:30.940 align:middle line:84%
this is more intuitive
or soul group guidance.

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:34.180 align:middle line:10%
They said, much of
what was forecast

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:36.940 align:middle line:10%
by Edgar Cayce and
people such as him, Ruth

00:47:36.940 --> 00:47:39.790 align:middle line:10%
Montgomery and others,
those channels,

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:42.280 align:middle line:10%
to happen on this Earth in
terms of the Earth changes

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:44.800 align:middle line:10%
and where they would
occur would actually not

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:48.250 align:middle line:10%
occur as a result of the
shift of the consciousness

00:47:48.250 --> 00:47:51.230 align:middle line:10%
of the people on that land.

00:47:51.230 --> 00:47:53.990 align:middle line:84%
So what does that mean
to you, if anything?

00:47:53.990 --> 00:47:57.040 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Well, the particular
prophecies and how things are

00:47:57.040 --> 00:47:59.230 align:middle line:84%
going to shift I'm
not as familiar with.

00:47:59.230 --> 00:48:01.790 align:middle line:84%
But the idea that
things can change

00:48:01.790 --> 00:48:04.780 align:middle line:84%
if our consciousness changes
I resonate with greatly.

00:48:04.780 --> 00:48:07.150 align:middle line:84%
That's what we've been
talking about here mostly,

00:48:07.150 --> 00:48:09.820 align:middle line:84%
I guess, if that was
the outlook of all of us

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:13.672 align:middle line:84%
that we don't have to be
stuck in these mental ruts,

00:48:13.672 --> 00:48:15.130 align:middle line:84%
no matter who we
are, whether we're

00:48:15.130 --> 00:48:18.490 align:middle line:84%
on the left, the right, the
scientific, the spiritual,

00:48:18.490 --> 00:48:22.840 align:middle line:84%
and work our best to find
common understanding.

00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:25.240 align:middle line:84%
We still might end
up disagreeing,

00:48:25.240 --> 00:48:27.760 align:middle line:84%
but at least it'd be better
to have a common understanding

00:48:27.760 --> 00:48:30.670 align:middle line:90%
about what we disagree about.

00:48:30.670 --> 00:48:32.770 align:middle line:84%
What could that
consciousness change be?

00:48:32.770 --> 00:48:35.320 align:middle line:84%
I think it's almost precisely
what we've talked about

00:48:35.320 --> 00:48:38.770 align:middle line:84%
so far, that we don't have to
always live in the same way

00:48:38.770 --> 00:48:39.850 align:middle line:90%
that we live.

00:48:39.850 --> 00:48:42.233 align:middle line:90%
That alone could go miles.

00:48:42.233 --> 00:48:43.150 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Absolutely.

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:46.590 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: And then it does
become more complex beyond that.

00:48:46.590 --> 00:48:51.250 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we have many
multiple emotional things

00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:55.690 align:middle line:84%
in our human existence that make
it not a black and white issue.

00:48:55.690 --> 00:48:58.090 align:middle line:84%
But that further
implies that we have

00:48:58.090 --> 00:49:00.790 align:middle line:84%
to talk to each other
about those things

00:49:00.790 --> 00:49:04.230 align:middle line:84%
so that we don't go off the deep
end in one way or the other.

00:49:04.230 --> 00:49:06.760 align:middle line:84%
You know, that
matter of our culture

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:10.390 align:middle line:90%
becoming overly competitive--

00:49:10.390 --> 00:49:11.860 align:middle line:90%
I do believe that's the case.

00:49:11.860 --> 00:49:15.220 align:middle line:84%
But I think that if you go just
about anywhere in the country

00:49:15.220 --> 00:49:18.340 align:middle line:84%
and you talk to people
about how they are raised

00:49:18.340 --> 00:49:19.960 align:middle line:84%
and their own
values and so forth,

00:49:19.960 --> 00:49:24.100 align:middle line:84%
that you'd still find a lot
of cooperative understanding,

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:25.250 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:49:25.250 --> 00:49:28.810 align:middle line:84%
So even very conservative
traditional cultures

00:49:28.810 --> 00:49:31.640 align:middle line:84%
are going to have in it
caring for one another

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:34.790 align:middle line:84%
and the golden rule firmly
in their consciousness.

00:49:34.790 --> 00:49:38.053 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: It's mostly when you
get to the subject of economics

00:49:38.053 --> 00:49:39.220 align:middle line:90%
where it's really afflicted.

00:49:39.220 --> 00:49:40.090 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:49:40.090 --> 00:49:43.720 align:middle line:84%
And there it seems like we
have no mechanisms by which we

00:49:43.720 --> 00:49:47.710 align:middle line:84%
can say, can we work
this out without fighting

00:49:47.710 --> 00:49:48.697 align:middle line:90%
over the goodies?

00:49:48.697 --> 00:49:49.780 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right, exactly.

00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:50.350 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:49:50.350 --> 00:49:52.930 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So do you think we
have to say goodbye to the day

00:49:52.930 --> 00:49:55.480 align:middle line:90%
of the 3,000-mile Caesar salad?

00:49:55.480 --> 00:49:58.240 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Oh, the
3,000-miles Caesar salad.

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:01.690 align:middle line:84%
I think that would be a great
thing to work our way back

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:03.670 align:middle line:90%
to much more local food.

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:04.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, definitely.

00:50:04.510 --> 00:50:09.080 align:middle line:84%
And right now, it'd be very
difficult to do it overnight,

00:50:09.080 --> 00:50:10.770 align:middle line:84%
especially, say,
here in Colorado

00:50:10.770 --> 00:50:14.860 align:middle line:84%
where I think the figure is
that we only eat 4% of our food

00:50:14.860 --> 00:50:17.020 align:middle line:90%
here comes from Colorado.

00:50:17.020 --> 00:50:19.110 align:middle line:84%
So we're a long
ways from creating

00:50:19.110 --> 00:50:23.100 align:middle line:84%
a food system that would feed
us here, even in Boulder County.

00:50:23.100 --> 00:50:24.810 align:middle line:84%
Part of that is
recognizing that we live

00:50:24.810 --> 00:50:27.390 align:middle line:90%
in a really arid environment.

00:50:27.390 --> 00:50:30.270 align:middle line:84%
And so we'd have
to maybe not expect

00:50:30.270 --> 00:50:32.440 align:middle line:84%
to have so much
food created there.

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:34.560 align:middle line:84%
But the other one would
be developing mechanisms

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:38.480 align:middle line:84%
by which we can produce a
healthy, sustainable food here,

00:50:38.480 --> 00:50:39.280 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:50:39.280 --> 00:50:41.610 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: What, also,
about the notion of grazing?

00:50:41.610 --> 00:50:43.200 align:middle line:84%
Just we only have a
few minutes left--

00:50:43.200 --> 00:50:44.760 align:middle line:84%
kind of looking
into that subject

00:50:44.760 --> 00:50:48.810 align:middle line:84%
because you have every kind of
argument and counterargument

00:50:48.810 --> 00:50:50.070 align:middle line:90%
and such coming out about it.

00:50:50.070 --> 00:50:53.190 align:middle line:84%
What is your position on
grazing and ultimately

00:50:53.190 --> 00:50:55.500 align:middle line:84%
where we have to go
with our food sources

00:50:55.500 --> 00:50:58.590 align:middle line:84%
out of concern for
our interrelationship

00:50:58.590 --> 00:50:59.460 align:middle line:90%
with the Earth?

00:50:59.460 --> 00:51:01.050 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Grazing in terms of--

00:51:01.050 --> 00:51:01.670 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Cattle grazing--

00:51:01.670 --> 00:51:02.210 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: --meat production.

00:51:02.210 --> 00:51:03.960 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: --for meat
industries and such,

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:06.480 align:middle line:84%
without getting political
about it because every body is

00:51:06.480 --> 00:51:08.022 align:middle line:84%
different and needs
different things.

00:51:08.022 --> 00:51:08.822 align:middle line:90%
I get that.

00:51:08.822 --> 00:51:09.660 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:51:09.660 --> 00:51:13.290 align:middle line:84%
Well, my sense on the
idea of animal agriculture

00:51:13.290 --> 00:51:16.310 align:middle line:84%
is very similar to a lot of
what we've been talking about.

00:51:16.310 --> 00:51:18.120 align:middle line:84%
A, let's talk to each
other and figure out

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:20.578 align:middle line:84%
the best ways of doing things
and not fight with each other

00:51:20.578 --> 00:51:23.070 align:middle line:84%
and leave all the solutions
left at the wayside.

00:51:23.070 --> 00:51:26.520 align:middle line:84%
And right now, my own
personal read on it

00:51:26.520 --> 00:51:29.460 align:middle line:84%
is that we can't eat
meat at the level

00:51:29.460 --> 00:51:32.460 align:middle line:84%
that we're doing it now
across the Earth and more

00:51:32.460 --> 00:51:34.650 align:middle line:84%
and more meat because
it just won't work.

00:51:34.650 --> 00:51:37.920 align:middle line:84%
We're going to despoil the
land upon which we depend.

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:40.260 align:middle line:84%
However, it doesn't
mean necessarily

00:51:40.260 --> 00:51:41.620 align:middle line:90%
that we can't eat any meat.

00:51:41.620 --> 00:51:45.930 align:middle line:84%
And also, we should remember
that the grazing of ungulates

00:51:45.930 --> 00:51:51.930 align:middle line:84%
was and is a part of the
land all across our world

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:57.000 align:middle line:84%
and that if you biomimic the
way that wild ungulates live

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:01.320 align:middle line:84%
that you can, in fact, improve
soil quality in an area

00:52:01.320 --> 00:52:03.420 align:middle line:84%
if we don't expect
too much from it.

00:52:03.420 --> 00:52:08.100 align:middle line:84%
So we can produce some meat for
people, probably plenty of meat

00:52:08.100 --> 00:52:12.390 align:middle line:84%
for people, and still improve
the quality of the land

00:52:12.390 --> 00:52:13.860 align:middle line:90%
there if we do it right.

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:18.300 align:middle line:84%
But that won't work if we expect
more and more and more steaks

00:52:18.300 --> 00:52:19.150 align:middle line:90%
and hamburgers.

00:52:19.150 --> 00:52:19.950 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: OK.

00:52:19.950 --> 00:52:22.320 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a very
rational answer to that.

00:52:22.320 --> 00:52:24.860 align:middle line:84%
And do you believe
that there is a place,

00:52:24.860 --> 00:52:28.410 align:middle line:84%
again, more on almost a
psycho-spiritual level,

00:52:28.410 --> 00:52:32.040 align:middle line:84%
for real communication between
communion between ourselves

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:35.040 align:middle line:84%
and nature, real
clarity of communion?

00:52:35.040 --> 00:52:38.160 align:middle line:84%
What do you see as the
importance of that in society,

00:52:38.160 --> 00:52:39.460 align:middle line:90%
now, reintroducing that?

00:52:39.460 --> 00:52:40.260 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Yeah.

00:52:40.260 --> 00:52:42.390 align:middle line:84%
I do think it's
possible for us to have

00:52:42.390 --> 00:52:44.160 align:middle line:90%
a communion with nature.

00:52:44.160 --> 00:52:47.100 align:middle line:84%
And in my own mind,
that's a recognition

00:52:47.100 --> 00:52:50.370 align:middle line:84%
that we are nature, that
we came out of this Earth,

00:52:50.370 --> 00:52:54.100 align:middle line:84%
and that we're a seamless
part of Earth as a whole.

00:52:54.100 --> 00:52:55.920 align:middle line:84%
And if we do that,
when we recognize

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:59.280 align:middle line:84%
that we can be in nature
when we're inside,

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:01.830 align:middle line:84%
but we can also be
outside more to be

00:53:01.830 --> 00:53:08.930 align:middle line:84%
in contact with those forces and
situations that we grew up in.

00:53:08.930 --> 00:53:14.330 align:middle line:84%
Our ancestors probably spent 95%
of their waking hours outside.

00:53:14.330 --> 00:53:18.550 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we could benefit
from that kind of situation.

00:53:18.550 --> 00:53:22.860 align:middle line:84%
But we can do so by
letting our minds

00:53:22.860 --> 00:53:26.880 align:middle line:84%
be open to lots of different
ways of connecting,

00:53:26.880 --> 00:53:30.060 align:middle line:84%
which would include a rational
thought about things, which

00:53:30.060 --> 00:53:35.790 align:middle line:84%
would include a non-rational
contemplation about life,

00:53:35.790 --> 00:53:37.290 align:middle line:90%
a mix of the two.

00:53:37.290 --> 00:53:39.460 align:middle line:84%
Slowing down, I think,
is a part of it.

00:53:39.460 --> 00:53:41.310 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: That's a big one for
you is just slow the heck down.

00:53:41.310 --> 00:53:42.477 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: That slowing down--

00:53:42.477 --> 00:53:45.630 align:middle line:84%
I think we're way off the charts
in terms of our pace of life.

00:53:45.630 --> 00:53:50.370 align:middle line:84%
So we can't even consider
how to do any of the above.

00:53:50.370 --> 00:53:53.580 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And one of the things
that's been proven in brain

00:53:53.580 --> 00:53:56.670 align:middle line:84%
science is the
role of gratitude.

00:53:56.670 --> 00:53:58.710 align:middle line:84%
Does that have any
resonance for what you're

00:53:58.710 --> 00:54:00.490 align:middle line:90%
saying in this whole matrix?

00:54:00.490 --> 00:54:04.920 align:middle line:84%
>> OGLE: Boy, that has a lot
of resonance for me in both,

00:54:04.920 --> 00:54:08.710 align:middle line:84%
I guess you might call,
rational and non-rational ways.

00:54:08.710 --> 00:54:14.150 align:middle line:84%
First, just expressing gratitude
changes our way of being.

00:54:14.150 --> 00:54:16.770 align:middle line:84%
It puts us in a
different mindset.

00:54:16.770 --> 00:54:19.320 align:middle line:10%
And there's a woman named
Janine Benyus who came up

00:54:19.320 --> 00:54:22.260 align:middle line:10%
with the term
"biomimicry," and it's

00:54:22.260 --> 00:54:23.950 align:middle line:10%
become quite big these days.

00:54:23.950 --> 00:54:26.070 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of what we
talk about in biomimicry

00:54:26.070 --> 00:54:29.790 align:middle line:84%
is how to produce a
process or a product

00:54:29.790 --> 00:54:32.670 align:middle line:84%
based on looking at
something in nature.

00:54:32.670 --> 00:54:35.640 align:middle line:10%
But when she was
asked one time how

00:54:35.640 --> 00:54:39.450 align:middle line:10%
we could show self-restraint
in human life, what

00:54:39.450 --> 00:54:42.150 align:middle line:10%
is the biomimetic way
that we would do that,

00:54:42.150 --> 00:54:46.740 align:middle line:10%
her answer was by showing
thanks and gratitude.

00:54:46.740 --> 00:54:52.050 align:middle line:84%
She said it was our
human way of becoming

00:54:52.050 --> 00:54:56.348 align:middle line:84%
more attuned to the
cycles of life around us.

00:54:56.348 --> 00:54:58.140 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I think
that's a perfect answer,

00:54:58.140 --> 00:55:00.550 align:middle line:84%
and we're out of time, and
we couldn't have ended it any

00:55:00.550 --> 00:55:01.350 align:middle line:90%
better.

00:55:01.350 --> 00:55:03.017 align:middle line:84%
Martin, thank you so
much for your work,

00:55:03.017 --> 00:55:05.040 align:middle line:84%
and I do hope that
we can slow down,

00:55:05.040 --> 00:55:08.700 align:middle line:84%
we can begin talking to
each other, both rationally

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:12.090 align:middle line:84%
and in terms of the magic of
what we can create together.

00:55:12.090 --> 00:55:14.910 align:middle line:84%
As you said, this has to
be a co-creative process.

00:55:14.910 --> 00:55:17.040 align:middle line:84%
And so for mothers and
fathers, it's up to us

00:55:17.040 --> 00:55:19.710 align:middle line:84%
to start teaching our
children these principles

00:55:19.710 --> 00:55:21.430 align:middle line:90%
from the time they can talk.

00:55:21.430 --> 00:55:22.230 align:middle line:90%
>> OGLE: Right.

00:55:22.230 --> 00:55:22.710 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:55:22.710 --> 00:55:24.390 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Thank
you so much, Martin.

